  <subsection xml:id="sec-sec1-1-1-name">
    <title>Multiplying Polynomials</title>
    <p> It is easy to get lost in the mechanics of mathematic, so it is good to have a ``picture in your head'' of what the operations represent. One way to think of multiplying two things is that they are the length (<m>L</m>) and width (<m>W</m>) of a rectangle with area <m>A = L*W.</m>
    </p>
    <p>
    Try finding the area of the rectangle with length <m>(x-4)</m> and width <m>(x+3)</m> below by using the smaller boxes to record the area of each piece (Warning, some ``areas'' may be negative!):
    </p> 

    <table>
    <title></title>
    <tabular>
      <row>
          <cell> </cell> <cell bottom="minor"><m> x</m> </cell> <cell bottom="minor"> <m>-4</m></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
          <cell right="minor"><m> +3 </m></cell> <cell bottom="minor" right="minor"> </cell> <cell bottom="minor" right="minor"> </cell>
      </row>
      <row>
          <cell right="minor"><m> -4 </m></cell> <cell bottom="minor" right="minor"> </cell> <cell bottom="minor" right="minor"> </cell>
      </row>
    </tabular>
    </table>

    <p> Total area: </p>
    <p> How does the ``area'' of the rectangle relate to finding the product <m>(x-4)(x+3)</m> ? </p>


    <p>Try finding this area:</p>
    <table>
    <title></title>
    <tabular>
      <row>
          <cell> </cell> <cell bottom="minor"><m> x^2</m> </cell> <cell bottom="minor"> <m>-2x</m></cell> <cell bottom="minor"> <m>+5</m></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
          <cell right="minor"><m> x </m></cell> <cell bottom="minor" right="minor"> </cell>  <cell bottom="minor" right="minor"> </cell> <cell bottom="minor" right="minor"> </cell>
      </row>
      <row>
          <cell right="minor"> <m>+1</m></cell> <cell bottom="minor" right="minor"> </cell>  <cell bottom="minor" right="minor"> </cell> <cell bottom="minor" right="minor"> </cell>
      </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>

    <p> Total area: How does this area relate to finding the product <m>(x+1)\left(x^{2}-2 x+5\right)</m>? </p>

    <p> Here's a question for you to discuss in your groups:</p>
    <p> Can you figure out the dimensions of the rectangle below that gives an area of <m>x^{2}-5 x+6</m>? How do you know these are the correct dimensions? </p>

